The Math interface in Jolie does not directly support handling complex probability distributions like Normal Distribution or Poisson Distribution out of the box. However, you can model these distributions using mathematical functions and generate random numbers based on their properties.

For example, to simulate a Normal Distribution with mean μ and standard deviation σ, you can use the Box-Muller transform to generate two independent standard normal random variables and then apply the transformation:
```jolie
normalDistribution@MyMath( request )( response ) {
    // Generate two independent standard normal random numbers using Box-Muller transform
    real x, y;
    do {
        x = 2 * sqrt(-2.0 * log(random@Math(request)(response1))) * cos(2 * pi * random@Math(request)(response2));
        y = 2 * sqrt(-2.0 * log(random@Math(request)(response3))) * sin(2 * pi * random@Math(request)(response4));
    } while (x*x + y*y > 1); // ensure x^2 + y^2 <= 1

    response = response5 := sqrt(-2.0 * log(request.p)) / sqrt(2.0) * (x * request.sigma + y * request.mean);
}
```

To simulate a Poisson Distribution with rate λ, you can use the Poisson probability mass function:
```jolie
poissonDistribution@MyMath( request )( response ) {
    int k;
    real sum = 0.0;

    // Generate Poisson random number
    do {
        k = round(exp(request.lambda) * random@Math(request)(response1));
        sum += exp(-request.lambda) * pow(random@Math(request)(response1), k) / fact(k);
    } while (sum > request.p);

    response = k;
}
```

