To implement a simple queue using an array in Python, you can use two pointers: one for the front (head) of the queue and another for the rear (tail). When adding an element to the queue (enqueue), you put it at the end of the array and increment the rear pointer. When removing an element from the queue (dequeue), you shift all elements in front of it one position towards the rear, and decrement the head pointer. Here's a Python implementation:

```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self, max_size):
        self.queue = [None] * max_size
        self.head = 0
        self.rear = -1

    def is_full(self):
        return (self.rear + 1) % len(self.queue) == self.head

    def enqueue(self, item):
        if not self.is_full():
            self.rear += 1
            self.queue[self.rear] = item
        else:
            print("Queue is full!")

    def dequeue(self):
        if not self.is_empty():
            item = self.queue[self.head]
            self.head += 1
            return item
        else:
            print("Queue is empty!")

