In object-oriented programming, inheritance is implemented by creating a new class that is a subclass of an existing class. The subclass inherits properties and methods from the superclass. In Java for instance, you can implement inheritance as follows:

```java
// Define the superclass
class Animal {
  String name;
  void eat() {
    System.out.println("Animal is eating.");
  }
}

// Define the subclass
class Dog extends Animal {
  String breed;
  void bark() {
    System.out.println("Dog is barking.");
  }
}
```

In this example, `Dog` is a subclass of `Animal`. The `Dog` class inherits the `name` property and the `eat()` method from the `Animal` superclass. Additionally, the `Dog` class has its own `breed` property and `bark()` method.

